00:00:54.034 --> 00:00:56.514
DATA ON MORAL FOUNDATIONS

00:00:56.514 --> 00:01:09.907
In a series of papers [10,[15][16][17][18][19] Jonathan Haidt and coworkers have described moral foundation theory (MFT), an heuristically driven theory dealing with the foundations of moral psychology.

00:01:09.907 --> 00:01:18.899
Its aim is to understand statistically significant differences in moral valuations of social issues and their association to coordinates of a political spectrum.

00:01:18.899 --> 00:01:29.467
Following Kohlberg [20] and Gilligan [21] work in moral psychology in the western world tradition, dealt with the representation of moral issues in a two dimensional space.

00:01:29.467 --> 00:01:35.497
The first historically identified dimension is related to whether an action leads to harm and violence or not.

00:01:35.497 --> 00:01:41.227
Later, the existence of a second dimension, associated to justice and fairness was introduced.

00:01:41.227 --> 00:01:59.769
By analysis of literature extending across time, geography and scientific disciplines, Haidt and coworkers introduced the main ingredient that yields a foundation theory [10]: humans when classifying issues as either moral or immoral, navigate not in a two dimensional space, but in one that is at least five dimensional.

00:01:59.769 --> 00:02:09.024
Valuations along these dimensions, called foundations in the literature of moral psychology, are necessary to characterize the moral content of a given issue.

00:02:09.024 --> 00:02:23.017
Their striking quantitative result is extracted from massive amounts of data: as the political spectrum is traversed from liberal to conservative, there is an increase, from two to five, in the number of moral dimensions considered relevant to form opinions.

00:02:23.017 --> 00:02:32.597
Liberals regard (a) harm/violence and (b)justice/fairness, the previously identified dimensions, as the most relevant foundations.

00:02:32.597 --> 00:02:44.389
In addition, conservatives hold (c) in-group loyalty, (d) respect for authority and considerations about (e) purity or sanctity in a considerable higher position than liberals.

00:02:44.389 --> 00:02:53.832
That means that, independently of the semantic role of the attributes, it can be asserted that liberals rely on a different subset of moral foundations than conservatives.

00:02:53.832 --> 00:02:58.324
We here employ liberal in the manner defined in the USA as social liberal.

00:02:58.324 --> 00:03:00.808
The data we have analyzed were furnished by

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.542
Jonathan Haidt [10,22] [23] They were collected from the answers to a specially designed questionnaire aimed at probing opinions about morally relevant situations.

00:00:10.542 --> 00:00:20.910
For each of N = 14250 respondents, Haidt and coworkers extracted five dimensional moral vectors with components related to five Moral Foundations.

00:00:20.910 --> 00:00:30.277
