00:00:50.442 --> 00:00:52.934
STATISTICAL MECHANICS MODEL

00:00:52.934 --> 00:01:10.227
Agents exchange information in the form of fields h j = J j  Z  [1, 1] that represent the mean opinion of agent j on a large set of issues or, considering that the information exchange is much faster than the adaptation dynamics, the opinion agent j has about the mean issue.

00:01:10.227 --> 00:01:15.019
The mean issue is objective and it is described by a set of D numbers Z  S D .

00:01:15.019 --> 00:01:20.749
The relevant variables, representing the society, are the internal variables of the agents.

00:01:20.749 --> 00:01:23.742
Every agent j has two main properties.

00:01:23.742 --> 00:01:31.234
A) Its internal state is determined by a set of D weights J j (moral vector), which is invisible to other agents.

00:01:31.234 --> 00:01:41.152
B) The main hypothesis in this work is that while weights jointly code for prior experience, they are subject to change due to the social interactions through a learning mechanism.

00:01:41.152 --> 00:01:46.232
The vector Z changes in time reflecting social changes in moral parsing or values.

00:01:46.232 --> 00:01:54.374
We, however, consider that the adaptation dynamics of J j is much faster than the dynamics of Z and suppose the latter as being fixed.

00:01:54.374 --> 00:02:01.454
We also concentrate on D = 5, but it might be interesting to explore the consequences of using different values.

00:02:01.454 --> 00:02:07.672
The only interaction among agents comes from learning about the opinion fields of agents in their social neighborhood.

00:02:07.672 --> 00:02:12.314
Learning occurs in order to decrease the psychological discomfort due to dissent.

00:02:12.314 --> 00:02:21.082
Learning is described by a noisy gradient descent dynamics on a potential function describing a psychological cost of disagreement with each of its social neighbors.

00:02:21.082 --> 00:02:30.562
