VII.

00:01:02.095 --> 00:01:05.575
DISCUSSION: DIVERSITY OF COGNITIVE STYLES

00:01:05.575 --> 00:01:15.380
Statistics and reaction times permit identifying different cognitive styles with different effective dimensions or opinions about a mean issue (that we call Zeitgeist in [7]).

00:01:15.380 --> 00:01:24.735
Therefore given that people do present different cognitive styles and that they interact and learn from each other we expect that there will be people who hold different sets of moral values.

00:01:24.735 --> 00:01:28.653
Cultural wars will follow from diversity of cognitive styles.

00:01:28.653 --> 00:01:31.233
This is a semantic free conclusion.

00:01:31.233 --> 00:01:35.150
The model cannot distinguish between the different moral foundations.

00:01:35.150 --> 00:01:40.805
There must be another reason why some of the foundations are always present while others may be absent.

00:01:40.805 --> 00:01:48.535
Evolutionary arguments by Haidt go a long way in explaining why the harm/care and justice dimensions are more uniformly common.

00:01:48.535 --> 00:01:53.578
They may be found, to some extent in other primates [31,32].

00:01:53.578 --> 00:02:02.358
The emergence of the other dimensions, which seem to be present only in humans, are supposed to foster higher cooperation levels and ultra-social behavior.

00:02:02.358 --> 00:02:13.150
Suppose, as we do, these facts to be reasonable, then the question that emerges is why society has kept all types of cognitive styles and not only those that lead to a more cohesive society?

00:02:13.150 --> 00:02:19.568
A possibility is that different strategies within a society are useful to cope collectively with different challenges.

00:02:19.568 --> 00:02:26.923
Higher cooperation level gives higher fitness during times where current opinions lead to correct answers from a survival point of view.

00:02:26.923 --> 00:02:32.878
Conservative behavior would then be the fittest when maintaining current behavior is beneficial to the society.

00:02:32.878 --> 00:02:41.370
However, during times when current opinions are not guiding in the finding of useful answers, in a survival enhancing sense, a different perspective is needed.

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:47.113
A larger menu of choices may permit finding better alternatives in an efficiently distributed manner.

00:02:47.113 --> 00:02:50.800
When the Zeitgeist changes, due to external conditions, or due to

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.205
a new issue being introduced to the debate, a more liberal approach seems reasonable.

00:00:05.205 --> 00:00:11.372
The question, from the current perspective, is then translated to whether this behavior can be seen within our model.

00:00:11.372 --> 00:00:19.602
In figure 4 we presented a connection between agents characterized with a given  parameter and the political affiliation of the questionnaire respondents.

00:00:19.602 --> 00:00:27.832
A question that arises is why a lower but nonzero value of  was found for a peer pressure around  = 10 which is well inside the ordered phase?

00:00:27.832 --> 00:00:32.612
Why were not the ultra-liberals associated to a  right on the edge of the phase transition?

00:00:32.612 --> 00:00:37.242
Maybe the reason can be found in the dynamics of adaptation to the new Zeitgeist.

00:00:37.242 --> 00:00:49.785
We find from the simulations, within the appropriate  region, that at that value,   0.20  0.35 the characteristic time of re-adaptation to a new Zeitgeist has a minimum (see figure 9).

00:00:49.785 --> 00:00:56.840
The lower the conservatism of a population the less cohesiveness it will present in responding to external challenges as a group.

00:00:56.840 --> 00:01:00.145
There is no benefit in being more liberal than necessary.

00:01:00.145 --> 00:01:04.350
Ultra-liberals are not on the disordered phase, but in the ordered phase.

00:01:04.350 --> 00:01:11.580
They even are not at the border of the transition, they are in a way prevented from being on the disordered phase by critical slowing down.

00:01:11.580 --> 00:01:15.872
Closer to the border the system is softer but takes longer to rearrange.

00:01:15.872 --> 00:01:23.839
And from our results it seems that even the ultra-liberals observed in the data rely on some corroboration in order to construct their moral vector.

00:01:23.839 --> 00:01:24.819
VIII.

00:01:24.819 --> 00:01:27.262
CONCLUSIONS AND PERSPECTIVES

00:01:27.262 --> 00:01:32.092
The modeling of social systems has a long (and wellfought [1]) history.

00:01:32.092 --> 00:01:43.009
It might be surprising to some that a mathematical model can be constructed and directly confronted to data, replicating some statistical findings and making predictions borne out by observations.

00:01:43.009 --> 00:01:47.927
We believe that this is possible by setting the problem in the context of information theory.

00:01:47.927 --> 00:02:03.094
After relevant variables were identified, information about neurocognitive, psychological and social science was used to attribute a probability distribution for the variables, which is finally used to estimate relevant experimental signatures from order parameters.

00:02:03.094 --> 00:02:07.587
This is, ultimately, what is done in traditional areas of Physics.

00:02:07.587 --> 00:02:16.129
We have presented results from Monte Carlo numerical methods and analytical approximation schemes such as mean field for a model of interacting agents.

00:02:16.129 --> 00:02:21.484
These techniques are suited to study the collective or aggregate properties of our model of agents.

00:02:21.484 --> 00:02:27.902
Drastic changes in collective properties signal phase transitions and the emergence of different regimes of behavior.

00:02:27.902 --> 00:02:31.082
The neural networks of the agents are quite simple.

00:02:31.082 --> 00:02:36.199
The only way to know if exaggerated simplifications have been made is to compare with data.

00:02:36.199 --> 00:02:49.617
Even if not useful for heuristic confrontation, models may be be useful in their own right as laboratories where we develop intuition about the different methodologies needed to extract information from possible more complex models of the future.

00:02:49.617 --> 00:02:50.728
They help in formul

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.617
ating a set of questions that can be addressed experimentally and theoretically.

00:00:04.617 --> 00:00:10.697
By pointing out their own limitations, current models can bring us closer to more useful models in the future.

00:00:10.697 --> 00:00:27.777
The networks are not supposed to model the brain networks of individuals, but rather the fact that people integrate the different moral dimensions of an issue, weighted by their own views about the importance of each dimension, in order to reach conclusions in an intuitionist way rather than by using a rationalist if-then set of rules.

00:00:27.777 --> 00:00:33.082
A summary of conclusions about our results should first of all mention what we have not attempted to do.

00:00:33.082 --> 00:00:38.662
No mention of any evolutionary perspective of how the moral foundations came to be was presented.

00:00:38.662 --> 00:00:49.205
In particular it seems reasonable to agree about the possible enhanced fitness that may derive from increased social capital of a more ordered society but this should be central in future discussions.

00:00:49.205 --> 00:00:58.185
If this is granted, then we have to answer why lower social capital promoting cognitive strategies should be present and not have been eradicated by selection.

00:00:58.185 --> 00:01:04.790
Are liberals just free riders invading a society of authority/loyalty/purity respecting conservatives?

00:01:04.790 --> 00:01:14.957
Trying to stay aside of semantic interpretations, we give an evolutionary reason why cognitive styles compatible with liberal behavior are found in modern times and have not been purged.

00:01:14.957 --> 00:01:24.875
Reaction times of the society of agents show that it is consistent to call large  agents as conservatives, since they have a large equilibration time under changes of the Zeitgeist.

00:01:24.875 --> 00:01:31.392
On the flip side, small  is expected to correlate with liberal fast adapting behavior under the same changes.

00:01:31.392 --> 00:01:33.335
But this was common knowledge.

00:01:33.335 --> 00:01:37.765
What is the novelty of conservatives taking more time to re-adapt than liberals?

00:01:37.765 --> 00:01:42.420
We found that liberals do not correspond to a  = 0 cognitive style.

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:47.500
Not only conservatives, but also liberals are on the ordered side of the phase diagram.

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:51.905
But as we approach the disordered phase, critical slowing down sets in.

00:01:51.905 --> 00:01:57.985
So agents with  too small will also have large equilibration times and these have probably been eliminated.

00:01:57.985 --> 00:02:06.090
A compromise between being fast to re-adapt and having high social capital shapes the societies of agents that live in an ever changing environment.

00:02:06.090 --> 00:02:13.170
We have shown that different cognitive styles give rise through social interactions to different statistics about the opinion field h.

00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:22.600
The interactions are represented by a potential that although it was never intended to claim precise realism it captures several stylized features of human cognitive styles.

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:26.580
We have been cautious to allow agents to learn from opposing views.

00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:35.722
While this may not always occur in human interactions, there are certain windows of time where people acquire their moral values from their social network of interactions.

00:02:35.722 --> 00:02:44.320
Qualitative information from fMRI and psychological tests about cognitive properties have been used to construct the interactions but future work will have to refine the learning

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.392
algorithms.

00:00:01.392 --> 00:00:15.035
Agents in social networks have shown a better agreement with the experimental data than simulations in e.g. square lattices and the model successfully predicts what sort of connectivity is to be expected if the subjacent social network is complex.

00:00:15.035 --> 00:00:26.490
We feel that it is rather remarkable that from the answers of questionnaires and by postulating certain information exchange mechanisms something about the topology of the social interactions of a society can be inferred.

00:00:26.490 --> 00:00:28.382
Many questions are raised.

00:00:28.382 --> 00:00:37.562
While we are aware of the previous use of the term peer pressure, we have introduced a quantitative definition that might lead to experimental characterization and measurement.

00:00:37.562 --> 00:00:44.792
This might help deciding whether our concept is useless or not, but it is the nature of experimental work to help decide relevance.

00:00:44.792 --> 00:00:54.622
An interesting consequence of our approach and of the idea of peer pressure is that histograms of effective dimensions might change after external threats to a society are detected.

00:00:54.622 --> 00:01:04.140
From the properties of the model we can predict that the mean of histograms H(h) will increase and variances of the distribution will be reduced after external threats are detected.

00:01:04.140 --> 00:01:14.245
The model also predicts that societies that discuss a wider set of issues will move in an opposite direction, with a reduction of the mean of H(h) and an increase of its variance.

00:01:14.245 --> 00:01:28.212
Several methodological problems are raised and should be analyzed, among them, the measurement of the peer pressure, the parsing of moral discourse into 5 or more dimensional vectors, the determination of the Zeitgeist vector, time scales of change.

00:01:28.212 --> 00:01:37.980
Among the theoretical topics, we should approach the problem of semantics and dress the different moral dimension of the model with an interpretation in the language of moral philosophers.

00:01:37.980 --> 00:01:43.410
Evolutionary considerations will probably guide the process and break the remaining symmetries.

00:01:43.410 --> 00:01:51.765
We have also neither addressed a possible role of genetic factors influencing cognitive styles nor if the value of  depends on the agent's environment.

00:01:51.765 --> 00:01:56.070
For the latter we will have to consider more sophisticated learning algorithms.

00:01:56.070 --> 00:02:03.987
Understanding evolutionary and cognitive influences behind cultural wars and their mathematical modeling seems to be a reachable goal.

